          src={heroImage}
          alt="Professional Airbnb turnover cleaning in Nashville Tennessee"
          width="896"
          height="504"
          loading="eager"
          fetchpriority="high"
          class="w-full rounded-t-2xl shadow-xl"
        />
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Main Content -->
  <article class="py-16 bg-white">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">

        <p class="text-xl text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-8">
          You wake up to a notification. A new review just posted for your Nashville Airbnb. You hold your breath and tap to read it.
        </p>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          "Great location, but the place wasn't as clean as expected. Found hair in the bathroom and the kitchen counters felt sticky. 3 stars."
        </p>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Your stomach drops. Three stars. From one bad turnover. And now that review sits there for every potential guest to see, dragging down your average, killing your bookings, threatening your Superhost status.
        </p>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          If you're hosting in Nashville's competitive short-term rental market—whether in East Nashville, the Gulch, Germantown, or anywhere in Music City—cleanliness isn't just important. It's everything. One cleaning failure can cost you thousands in lost bookings.
        </p>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Let's talk about how to never let that happen.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6">Why Cleanliness Reviews Hit Different</h2>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Guests will forgive a lot. A slightly uncomfortable mattress? They'll mention it but won't destroy your rating. Slow WiFi? Minor complaint. Street noise? They knew they were booking downtown Nashville.
        </p>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          But cleanliness failures? Those feel personal. They feel disrespectful. Guests think: "This host doesn't care about me."
        </p>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Airbnb knows this. That's why they broke out cleanliness as its own rating category. A low cleanliness score tanks your visibility in search results faster than anything else.
        </p>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          The math is brutal: in a market like Nashville with thousands of listings, guests filter by rating. Anything below 4.7 gets buried. One bad cleanliness review can drop you below that threshold and cost you weeks of bookings.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6">The Nashville Airbnb Cleaning Challenge</h2>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Nashville presents unique challenges for short-term rental cleaning:
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">High Volume Tourism</h3>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Nashville draws 15+ million visitors annually. CMA Fest, NFL games, Broadway tourism, bachelorette parties—the city runs at high capacity much of the year. That means:
        </p>

        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-8 space-y-3 text-lg text-gray-600">
          <li>Tight turnovers: Same-day checkout/check-in is common</li>
          <li>Heavy use: Party groups wear on properties differently than business travelers</li>
          <li>Back-to-back bookings: No days off for deep cleaning</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">The Bachelorette Factor</h3>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Nashville is the bachelorette party capital of America. These groups can be great guests—they book multiple rooms, they're there to have fun. But they also leave:
        </p>

        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-8 space-y-3 text-lg text-gray-600">
          <li>Glitter. Everywhere. (It multiplies, somehow.)</li>
          <li>Makeup stains on towels, robes, sometimes walls</li>
          <li>Spilled drinks on furniture and rugs</li>
          <li>Heavy loads on bathrooms and linens</li>
        </ul>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Your cleaning process needs to handle the aftermath.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">Seasonal Extremes</h3>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Tennessee weather means seasonal cleaning challenges:
        </p>

        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-8 space-y-3 text-lg text-gray-600">
          <li><strong>Spring:</strong> Pollen coats everything—outdoor furniture, window sills, tracked-in dust</li>
          <li><strong>Summer:</strong> Humidity leads to musty smells if not addressed</li>
          <li><strong>Fall:</strong> Leaves tracked in, allergens from yard debris</li>
          <li><strong>Winter:</strong> Salt and road grime at entries, drier air affects dust</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6">The Turnover Cleaning Checklist</h2>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Here's what professional Airbnb turnover cleaning should include. This is the standard we hold ourselves to for Nashville-area properties:
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">Kitchen</h3>

        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-8 space-y-3 text-lg text-gray-600">
          <li>All dishes washed and put away (check the dishwasher for forgotten items)</li>
          <li>Countertops sanitized—not just wiped, actually sanitized</li>
          <li>Appliance exteriors cleaned (fingerprints on stainless are obvious)</li>
          <li>Inside microwave cleaned (guests always open it)</li>
          <li>Coffee maker cleaned and ready with fresh supplies</li>
          <li>Refrigerator checked—remove all guest items, wipe down</li>
          <li>Sink and faucet gleaming</li>
          <li>Trash replaced with fresh bag</li>
          <li>Floor swept and mopped</li>
          <li>Check drawers for forgotten items or mess</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">Bathrooms</h3>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          This is where reviews are won and lost. The bathroom needs to be hotel-level clean:
        </p>

        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-8 space-y-3 text-lg text-gray-600">
          <li>Toilet thoroughly cleaned—inside bowl, under rim, exterior, base</li>
          <li>Shower/tub scrubbed, including grout and glass doors</li>
          <li>Drain cleared of hair (guests notice this immediately)</li>
          <li>Mirror streak-free</li>
          <li>Counter sanitized</li>
          <li>Fresh towels, hotel-style folded or rolled</li>
          <li>New toilet paper roll with visible fold</li>
          <li>Trash replaced</li>
          <li>Floor cleaned, including around toilet base</li>
          <li>Bath mat fresh</li>
          <li>Toiletries restocked and neatly arranged</li>
          <li>Check under cabinet for guest items</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">Bedrooms</h3>

        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-8 space-y-3 text-lg text-gray-600">
          <li>All linens changed—sheets, pillowcases, duvet covers</li>
          <li>Mattress inspected for stains (address immediately)</li>
          <li>Bed made with tight corners, pillows fluffed</li>
          <li>Nightstands cleared and wiped</li>
          <li>Lamps and outlets dust-free</li>
          <li>Dresser drawers checked for forgotten items</li>
          <li>Closet organized, hangers spaced evenly</li>
          <li>Mirror clean</li>
          <li>Floors vacuumed under bed and furniture</li>
          <li>Windows and blinds dust-free</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">Living Areas</h3>

        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-8 space-y-3 text-lg text-gray-600">
          <li>Couch cushions flipped/rotated, vacuumed</li>
          <li>TV screen wiped (fingerprints are visible)</li>
          <li>Remote controls sanitized (high-touch item)</li>
          <li>Coffee table and surfaces clear and clean</li>
          <li>Blankets and throws folded neatly</li>
          <li>Carpet vacuumed, hard floors mopped</li>
          <li>Check under furniture for trash or forgotten items</li>
          <li>Guest book and house manual organized</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">Throughout the Property</h3>

        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-8 space-y-3 text-lg text-gray-600">
          <li>All lights working (replace bulbs as needed)</li>
          <li>Thermostat set to welcome temperature</li>
          <li>All doors and windows locked, then unlocked per check-in instructions</li>
          <li>Smart lock codes updated if applicable</li>
          <li>Light switches and door handles sanitized</li>
          <li>Entry clean—shoes removed, mat shaken out</li>
          <li>Outdoor areas tidied (if included)</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6">The Details That Make Five-Star Reviews</h2>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Basic cleaning gets you four stars. These extras push you to five:
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">The Smell Test</h3>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Walk in like a guest. What's the first thing you smell? Nothing should smell bad, but it also shouldn't smell like heavy air freshener (that screams "covering something up").
        </p>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          The ideal: Clean. Fresh. Maybe a subtle, high-quality scent. Not competing fragrances.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">The White Glove Areas</h3>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Guests notice things cleaners skip:
        </p>

        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-8 space-y-3 text-lg text-gray-600">
          <li>Top of the refrigerator</li>
          <li>Baseboards near the entry</li>
          <li>Windowsills</li>
          <li>Ceiling fan blades</li>
          <li>Behind the toilet</li>
          <li>Light switch plates</li>
          <li>Under the couch cushions</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">The Photo Test</h3>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          After cleaning, take photos. Compare them to your listing photos. The space should look identical to what guests expect when they book.
        </p>

      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

